{"parse":{"title":"Matoi","pageid":7451046,"revid":703586626,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>A <b>matoi<span style=\"font-weight: normal\">&#32;(<span lang=\"ja\">\u7e8f</span><span style=\"display:none\">,</span>&#32;<i>matoi</i>, \u307e\u3068\u3044)</span></b> was a flag used in <a href=\"/wiki/Edo_period\" title=\"Edo period\">Edo period</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Japan\" title=\"Japan\">Japan</a> by firemen<span style=\"font-weight: normal\">&#32;(<span lang=\"ja\">\u706b\u6d88\u3057</span><span style=\"display:none\">,</span>&#32;<i>hikeshi</i>)</span> to notify people of a fire near or within a building. It was taken up on a roof near the burning building by the matoi holder<span style=\"font-weight: normal\">&#32;(<span lang=\"ja\">\u7e8f\u6301</span><span style=\"display:none\">,</span>&#32;<i>matoimochi</i>)</span> and waved to draw the attention of other groups of firefighters, who would then hurry to the site of the fire to assist. Each different group of firemen in the Edo period had their own matoi to identify themselves. In modern Japan, the matoi is only used for ceremonial purposes.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Matoi&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.nihonhikeshihozonkai.org/english/index.html\">Japan Hikeshi (Firemen) Preserving Foundation</a>,</li></ul>\n<table class=\"metadata plainlinks stub\" role=\"presentation\" style=\"background:transparent\"><tbody><tr><td><a href=\"/wiki/File:Flag_of_Japan.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Stub icon\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/9e/Flag_of_Japan.svg/25px-Flag_of_Japan.svg.png\" width=\"25\" height=\"17\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/9e